# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dean-kamen
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dean-kamen/10-mph] Dissatisfied with their average corporate jobs, filmmakers Weeks and Caldwell formed a production company, Spinning Blue, in Denver, Colorado prior to beginning production of *10 MPH*.
[src:dean-kamen/10-mph] They have discussed their lack of training and experience in the film industry, lack of investment capital to make the film, and lack of film industry contacts as challenges at the beginning of the process.
[src:dean-kamen/10-mph] Rather than pursuing traditional channels of film making, Weeks and Caldwell used the Web to raise funds and promote *10 MPH*.
[src:dean-kamen/10-mph] They conceived the idea of making a film before knowing what it would be about.
[src:dean-kamen/10-mph] Shortly thereafter, a friend gave them the idea of making a film involving a Segway.
[src:dean-kamen/10-mph] In 2004, Weeks and Caldwell purchased a Segway and decided to film a documentary about traveling across the United States at 10 miles per hour (16 km/h).
[src:dean-kamen/10-mph] Caldwell actually rode the scooter while Weeks directed and managed the film footage.
[src:dean-kamen/10-mph] Weeks and other members of the production crew followed Caldwell in a car with the film equipment.
[src:dean-kamen/10-mph] They used a Sony PD-150 to capture 180 hours of footage.
[src:dean-kamen/10-mph] Post-production occurred back in Denver after the Segway journey with involvement from other members of the Denver film community.
[src:dean-kamen/10-mph] The documentary received generally positive reviews from critics.
[src:dean-kamen/10-mph] Review aggregation website Rotten Tomatoes gives the film a score of 80 percent based on reviews from five critics, with a rating average of 7.4 out of 10.
[src:dean-kamen/10-mph] Of a more critical opinion, where *The Christian Science Monitor*, which commented, "The duo's hook for a movie is to document their gimmicky journey from Seattle to Boston on a Segway scooter.
[src:dean-kamen/10-mph] We never truly get inside the heads of these unlikely pioneers but scenic photography and lively side characters make for a diverting trip." On a similar note, Lisa Kennedy of the *Denver Post*, reflected that "the narration can be a tad earnest.
[src:dean-kamen/10-mph] In a favorable review in the *Boise Weekly*, Travis Estvold wrote, "Though piloting a Segway seems a bit gimmicky, it does what the filmmakers probably intended: It attracts plenty of attention.
[src:dean-kamen/10-mph] In an article on upcoming releases in 2007, the *Boston Globe* mentioned *10 MPH*, calling it an "amusingly offbeat documentary." In the *Idaho Statesman*, Chad Dryden remarked; “10 MPH succeeds on many levels.
[src:dean-kamen/10-mph] For one, it’s a terrific American travelogue, taking the viewer through small-town charm, purple mountain majesty and the big city’s vibrating pulse.
[src:dean-kamen/10-mph] The guys seem nice enough, and there are plenty of sweet slices of Americana, so you might find yourself torn.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] The primary election to select the candidates who appeared on the general election ballot took place on September 13, 2016.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] Incumbent Republican Senator Kelly Ayotte ran for re-election to a second term in office, and won the primary by a wide margin.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] Governor Maggie Hassan chose not to seek re-election to a third term as governor, and instead sought the nomination of the Democratic Party for the Senate.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] Hassan was unopposed in the Democratic primary and won the general election by 1,017 votes, representing a winning margin of approximately 0.14%.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] This made the election the closest race of the 2016 Senate election cycle, and also the closest race in a New Hampshire Senate election since the disputed 1974–75 election.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] Hassan became the first Democratic senator elected in this seat since the latter election and only the second since 1932, when a Democrat had last won a full term to this seat.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] The Democratic Party also flipped New Hampshire's 1st congressional district in the concurrent House election, thus marking the first time since 1854 that New Hampshire had an entirely Democratic congressional delegation.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] To date, this remains the last time that a Democratic candidate for Senate in New Hampshire has failed to win a majority of the vote or lost any county other than Belknap and Coös, and the last New Hampshire U.S.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] Senate race where the incumbent was defeated.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] Hassan was sworn in on January 3, 2017, marking the first time since 1979 that Democrats simultaneously held both of New Hampshire's Senate seats.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] Ayotte was predicted to face opposition in the primary from a Tea Party candidate.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] In October 2013, former New Hampshire Republican State Committee Chairman Jack Kimball said: "There is no question in my mind that she will garner a primary challenger".
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] Ultimately, she faced only token opposition and won the primary with more than 78% of the vote.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] On Saturday, January 16, 2016, the Libertarian Party of New Hampshire selected Brian Chabot as their nominee for the U.S.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] This was Ayotte's only defeat of her electoral career.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] Making a political comeback in 2024, she won that year's New Hampshire gubernatorial election.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] Hassan won one of the two congressional districts, and Ayotte won the other that also elected a Democrat.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] In February 2017, President Donald Trump (who had endorsed Ayotte) told a gathering of senators at the White House that fraudulent out-of-state voting had cost him and Ayotte the election in New Hampshire.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] On September 7, state House speaker Shawn Jasper (who also had endorsed Ayotte) alleged that voter fraud had swung the election.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] He made the allegations based on a report by the New Hampshire House of Representatives saying that of the 6,540 voters who had registered to vote on election day, only 1,014 had obtained a New Hampshire driver's license by August 30 of the following year.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] *The Washington Post* was able to quickly contact three such voters who said that they were college students and had kept the driver's license from their home state.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] Several investigations by New Hampshire's Ballot Law Commission found no evidence of widespread fraud, and only four total instances of fraud in the state for the 2016 elections.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] Specifically addressing the claim of people being bussed in from out of state to vote, Associate Attorney General Anne Edwards noted that they found no evidence for such claims.
[src:dean-kamen/2016-united-states-senate-election-in-new-hampshire] When they investigated these claims, they found that the buses were chartered out of state, but the voters on the buses lived in New Hampshire and could legally vote there.
[src:dean-kamen/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen graduated from Thomas Jefferson High School in San Antonio, Texas.
[src:dean-kamen/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He received a Bachelor of Science degree from Texas A&M University in 1952, a Master of Science degree from Stevens Institute of Technology in 1958, and an honorary doctorate from Stevens in 1982.
[src:dean-kamen/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen joined NASA in 1962 and served in key leadership roles critical to the success of the flights and lunar landings of the Apollo Program.
[src:dean-kamen/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] From 1969 to 1972, Cohen was the manager for the Apollo Command and Service Modules.
[src:dean-kamen/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He oversaw the design, development, production and test flights of the Space Shuttles as manager of NASA's Space Shuttle Orbiter Project Office from 1972 to 1982.
[src:dean-kamen/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After serving as Director of Engineering at Johnson for several years, he was named director of the center in 1986, serving in that post until 1993.
[src:dean-kamen/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After his retirement from NASA, Cohen taught mechanical engineering design at Texas A&M University.
[src:dean-kamen/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] In 2000, he was appointed Professor Emeritus, and in 2010, he was awarded an honorary Doctor of Letters.
[src:dean-kamen/aerial-assist] The Kickoff event was held on January 4, 2014.
[src:dean-kamen/aerial-assist] Speakers included Dean Kamen and Woodie Flowers.
[src:dean-kamen/aerial-assist] It was broadcast on NASA TV beginning at 10:30 EST.
[src:dean-kamen/aerial-assist] In the game, the alliances win via getting the scoring elements (2'-diameter exercise balls) into the scoring areas located on the far end of the field.
[src:dean-kamen/aerial-assist] The game starts with each robots in either the White Zone (center field) or the goalie zones.
[src:dean-kamen/aerial-assist] They can be preloaded with 1 game ball prior to the start.
[src:dean-kamen/aerial-assist] The match begins with a 10-second autonomous period, where robots use the pre-programmed instructions to score points.
[src:dean-kamen/aerial-assist] Said points are worth 5 more during the Autonomous period, and one goal will be lit up ("hot") during each half.
[src:dean-kamen/aerial-assist] That goal is worth 5 additional points, for a maximum total of a 10-point bonus.
[src:dean-kamen/aerial-assist] In addition, every robot that moves from the center to their own side of the field earns another five point bonus.
[src:dean-kamen/aerial-assist] When Tele-op starts, the teams take control of their respective robots.
[src:dean-kamen/aerial-assist] The cycle starts when a human player transfers a ball onto the playing field.
[src:dean-kamen/aerial-assist] The robots can then do either the basic goal score (take the ball to the other end of the field), or assist them in doing so.
[src:dean-kamen/aerial-assist] The recipient of the latter will earn bonus points (2 assists=10 points, 3 assists=30 points).
[src:dean-kamen/aerial-assist] Throwing the ball over the truss (the midpoint overhang) when transferring, a la volleyball, will add 10 additional points.
[src:dean-kamen/aerial-assist] Having an alliance partner catch it will earn 10 more points.
[src:dean-kamen/aerial-assist] A robot in the goalie zones can block shots via extending upwards.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] Aim High was played by two alliances, red and blue, each consisting of three robots.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] During a 10-second autonomous mode robots were programmed to score into any of the three goals: one raised center goal marked by a green vision target and two corner goals at floor level.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] At the end of the autonomous period the alliance with the most points would gain a 10-point bonus and would be placed on defense for round two.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] Rounds two, three and four were each 40 seconds long and were human-controlled rounds.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] Between rounds two and three the alliances switch from offense to defense or vice versa.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] At the start of round 4 any alliance could score into the corresponding goals.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] At the end of the match any alliance could receive bonus points by placing its three robots on a platform below the center goal.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] The Aim High field had 6 goals and 2 platforms.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] Unlike previous years an alliance's goals were on the far side of the field.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] The field was flat and measures 54 feet (16 m) long by 26 feet (7.9 m) wide.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] The alliance station wall was 26 ft (8 m) long and stretched the width of the field.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] The middle 18 ft (5 m) of the alliance station wall was made of "diamond plate" aluminum from the floor to 3 ft (1 m) high with clear acrylic filling the rest of the 3.5 ft (1.1 m).
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] The outer edges of the wall consisted of transparent polycarbonate.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] Above each alliance station there was a circular goal (the center goal), with a green light above it.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] The green light was used so that the CMUcam can lock onto it.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] On the bottom left and right of each alliance station there were two rectangular holes, the corner goals, through which balls can be maneuvered to receive points.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] In front of each alliance station there was a raised platform.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] The tournament structure was the same as in previous years.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] In the regional competitions teams were given access to their robots on the Thursday of the competition weekend.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] It was a practice day giving each team a number of practice rounds on the regulation playing field.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] Friday and the morning of Saturday was dedicated to a series of qualification rounds.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] Each team competed in around seven to ten matches.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] The number of wins by a team in those matches determined the team's ranking.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] Before a lunch break on Saturday the top eight teams from the qualification rounds were asked, in order from the top-seeded team to the eighth seed, to select an alliance of three robots.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] In contrast to previous years this order reversed for the second selection round and the eighth seed picks first and then backwards to the first seed.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] This was instituted to make the finals more competitive and balanced compared to previous years.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] After the lunch break the finals took place.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] This was a standard-elimination tournament bracket starting with alliance 1 facing alliance 8, alliance 2 facing alliance 7, and so on.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] At the end of the finals the last remaining alliance was declared the winner and all three teams were given the right to attend the national competition.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] There were many viable tactics in Aim High.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] There were ball dumpers, floor shooters, ramp shooters and defensive robots.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] The primary aim of a ball dumper was to collect balls that were either loaded into it via the human players or that it collected off the floor.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] The ball dumper then moved to one of the lower goals and dumped all the balls into the lower goal for a significant number of 1-point goals.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] Ball dumpers could be made to be very reliable in autonomous, as they do not depend on aiming and were difficult to block with an opposing ramming robot from across the field.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] Ball dumping teams had to deal with defensive robots attempting to block their transit to and from the human loading zone, as well as teams that may simply block the lower goals to prevent them from dumping.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] Floor shooters were the more common of the two shooter varieties.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] A majority fired mainly from a few feet in front of the ramp.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] Some (referred to as ranged shooters, perimeter shooters or distant shooters) could fire from half the court distance or more.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] Floor shooters, especially those that fired from near the ramp, had to contend with great amount of defense to block their shots and dislocate them from shooting positions.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] A wide variety of shooting mechanisms could be found on floor shooters including two horizontally mounted spinning discs, two vertically mounted (for the allowance of backspin), and singular mount spinning discs with a curved output track.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] Many used the CMUCam to some extent while shooting and a few even had automated turrets that automatically locked onto the target.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] Ramp shooters were robots that used the height of the ramp to greatly reduce the distance that they had to propel the ball.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] Ramp shooters drive up to their wall and fire balls through a high-mounted shooting mechanism that is statically aimed directly at the goal.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] Ramp shooters had a disadvantage from floor shooters as they had to traverse the ramp, risking tipping, and could only shoot from one location directly in front of the goal.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] Defense against a ramp shooter was simply to sit in position on top of the ramp, or prevent them from getting up the ramp.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] Since scoring in the high goal in "Aim High" was difficult and as there were specific offense and defense periods defense plays a very large role.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] An effective defense prevented their opponents from gathering balls, dumping balls and shooting balls.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] A defensive robot was involved in a great deal of ramming and pushing and had to have a very strong and durable drivetrain.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] A low centre of mass was a key asset so that the robot could play up and down the ramp without worry of tipping.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] In order to prevent robots from scoring a robot playing defense will attempt to attack the corners of the shooting robot, which would cause it to spin.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] A few defensive bots had nets, walls or other defensive mechanisms to block shots.
[src:dean-kamen/aim-high] The championship was held in the Georgia Dome, Atlanta.
[src:dean-kamen/alan-howard-engineer] Howard was born in Washington, D.C., in 1905.
[src:dean-kamen/alan-howard-engineer] He obtained his BSc in electrical engineering from Purdue University in 1927.
[src:dean-kamen/alan-howard-engineer] After his graduation in 1927, Howard started his lifelong career at the General Electric Company in Schenectady, New York as electrical engineer.
[src:dean-kamen/alan-howard-engineer] He advanced rapidly various positions, and moved into steam turbine activities in 1941.
[src:dean-kamen/alan-howard-engineer] In World War II at General Electric, Howard managed the development of aircraft gas turbine engine for the United States Air Force, and developed the TG 100 and TG 180 turboprop engine.
[src:dean-kamen/alan-howard-engineer] Coffin Award by General Electric for his "accomplishments in connection with the design and development of the TG100 and TG180 aircraft gas turbines." In 1954, he was awarded the honorary degree of doctor of engineering by Purdue University.
[src:dean-kamen/alan-howard-engineer] In 1962, he had been elected Fellow of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, and in 1964, he was awarded the ASME Medal.
[src:dean-kamen/asme-medal] The **ASME Medal**, created in 1920, is the highest award bestowed by the ASME (founded as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers) Board of Governors for "eminently distinguished engineering achievement".
[src:dean-kamen/asme-medal] The award has been presented every year since 1996 (first medalist was awarded in 1921), and it consists of a $15,000 honorarium, a certificate, a travel supplement not to exceed $750, and a gold medal inscribed with the words, "What is not yet, may be".
[src:dean-kamen/asme-medal] ASME also gives out a number of other awards yearly, including the Edwin F.
[src:dean-kamen/asme-medal] Church Medal, the Holley medal, and the Soichiro Honda medal.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] Dean Lawrence Kamen was born on April 5, 1951, on Long Island, New York, to Jack Kamen and Evelyn Kamen (born Rothenberg).
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] His father was an illustrator for *Mad*, *Weird Science*, and other EC Comics publications.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] During his teenage years, Kamen was already being paid for his ideas; local bands and museums paid him to build light and sound systems.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] His annual earnings reached $60,000 before his high school graduation.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] He attended Worcester Polytechnic Institute, but quit in 1976 before graduating, after five years of private advanced research for the insulin pump AutoSyringe.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] Kamen is known best for inventing the product that eventually became known as the Segway PT, an electric, self-balancing human transporter with a computer-controlled gyroscopic stabilization and control system.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] The device is balanced on two parallel wheels and is controlled by moving body weight.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] The machine's development was the object of much speculation and hype after segments of a book quoting Steve Jobs and other notable information technology visionaries espousing its society-revolutionizing potential were leaked in December 2001.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] Kamen was already a successful inventor: his company *Auto Syringe* manufactures and markets the first drug infusion pump.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] Kamen has worked extensively on a project involving Stirling engine designs, attempting to create two machines: one that would generate power, and the Slingshot that would serve as a water purification system.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] He hopes the project will help improve living standards in developing countries.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] Kamen has a patent on his water purifier, and other patents pending.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] In 2014, the film *SlingShot* was released, detailing Kamen's quest to use his vapor compression distiller to fix the world's water crisis.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] Kamen is also the co-inventor of a compressed air device that would launch a human into the air in order to quickly launch SWAT teams or other emergency workers to the roofs of tall, inaccessible buildings.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] In 2009 Kamen stated that his company DEKA was now working on solar powered inventions.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] Kamen and DEKA also developed the DEKA Arm System or "Luke", a prosthetic arm replacement that offers its user much more fine motor control than traditional prosthetic limbs.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] It was approved for use by the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) in May 2014, and DEKA is looking for partners to mass-produce the prosthesis.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] In 1989, Kamen founded FIRST (For Inspiration and Recognition of Science and Technology), an organization intended to build students' interests in science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM).
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] In 1992, working with MIT Professor Emeritus Woodie Flowers, Kamen created the FIRST Robotics Competition (FRC), which evolved into an international competition that by 2020 had drawn 3,647 teams and more than 91,000 students.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] In 2017, FIRST held its first Olympics-style competition – FGC (FIRST Global Challenge) – in Washington, D.C.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] In 2010, Kamen called FIRST the invention he is most proud of, and said that 1 million students had taken part in the contests.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] On January 31, 2026, Kamen was put on a leave of absence due to his ties with Jeffrey Epstein.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] On March 11, 2026, Kamen voluntarily resigned from the FIRST Board of Directors and withdrew from all FIRST activities.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] In 2017, Kamen founded the Advanced Regenerative Manufacturing Institute along with McCoy Mathies (ARMI) and launched BioFabUSA, a Manufacturing USA Innovation Institute with an $80 million grant from the Department of Defense.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] BioFabUSA's mission is to "...*make practical the large-scale manufacturing of engineered tissues and tissue-related technologies, to benefit existing industries and grow new ones*".
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] In addition to DoD funding, Kamen brought together a consortium of private sector entities to form a public-private partnership which pledged $214M additional private dollars.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] He was elected to the National Academy of Engineering in 1997 for inventing and commercializing biomedical devices and fluid measurement and control systems, and for popularizing engineering among young people.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] In 1999 he was awarded the 5th Annual Heinz Award in Technology, the Economy and Employment, and in 2000 received the National Medal of Technology from then President Clinton for inventions that have advanced medical care worldwide.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] In April 2002, Kamen was awarded the Lemelson-MIT Prize for inventors, for his invention of the Segway and of an infusion pump for diabetics.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] In 2003 his "Project Slingshot", an inexpensive portable water purification system, was named a runner-up for "coolest invention of 2003" by *Time* magazine.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] In 2005 he was inducted into the National Inventors Hall of Fame for his invention of the AutoSyringe.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] In 2006 Kamen was awarded the "Global Humanitarian Action Award" by the United Nations.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] In 2015, Kamen received an honorary Doctor of Engineering and Technology degree from Yale University.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] In 2017, Kamen was honored with an institutional honorary degree from Université de Sherbrooke.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] Kamen received the Stevens Honor Award on November 6, 2009, given by the Stevens Institute of Technology and the Stevens Alumni Association.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] On November 14, 2013, he received the James C.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] Kamen received the 2018 Public Service Award from the National Science Board, honoring his exemplary public service and contributions to the public's understanding of science and engineering.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] In 2007, his residence was a hexagonal, shed style mansion he dubbed Westwind, located in Bedford, New Hampshire, just outside Manchester.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] Kamen owns and pilots an Embraer Phenom 300 light jet aircraft and three Enstrom helicopters, including a 280FX, a 480, and a 480B.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] He regularly commutes to work via his helicopters and had a hangar built into his house.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] In 2016 he flew as a passenger in a B-2 Spirit bomber at Whiteman AFB, marking the opening of the 2016 FRC World Championship in St.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] He is the main subject of *Code Name Ginger: the Story Behind Segway and Dean Kamen's Quest to Invent a New World*, a nonfiction narrative book by journalist Steve Kemper published by Harvard Business School Press in 2003 (released in paperback as *Reinventing the Wheel*).
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] Kamen is a member of the USA Science and Engineering Festival's Advisory Board and is also a member of the Xconomists, an ad hoc team of editorial advisors for the tech news and media company, Xconomy.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] He is also on the Board of Trustees of the X Prize Foundation.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] In the 2016 United States Senate election in New Hampshire, Kamen endorsed Kelly Ayotte, appearing in an ad supporting her.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] Kamen appeared in photographs from the estate of Jeffrey Epstein that were released to the public in December 2025, where he was shown with Epstein and Richard Branson on what appears to be a beach.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] Kamen stated that the pictures were probably from Branson's Necker Island, and claimed to have no connection with Epstein.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] His name had earlier appeared in the 2003 flight logs of Epstein's private jet.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] Further documents released in January 2026 included references to Kamen visiting Epstein's island and records of multiple phone calls and meetings between the two men.
[src:dean-kamen/dean-kamen] Kamen employed Nadia Marcinko as a flight trainer at DEKA.
